1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,580
Okay, good morning. We are
doing Mesopotamia today.

2
00:00:02,840 --> 00:00:04,160
This is the Bronze Age.

3
00:00:04,540 --> 00:00:06,120
We did Egypt last class.

4
00:00:06,220 --> 00:00:10,540
We are doing Mesopotamia today. In the next
class, we will finish with the Indus Valley.

5
00:00:11,580 --> 00:00:13,180
So, before I begin,

6
00:00:13,560 --> 00:00:19,180
I want to make three general
points about the study of history

7
00:00:19,180 --> 00:00:21,180
and how civilizations develop.

8
00:00:22,180 --> 00:00:23,500
The first point is this.

9
00:00:26,440 --> 00:00:29,940
Every culture has a mythology.

10
00:00:31,600 --> 00:00:34,120
And the mythology is the

11
00:00:34,120 --> 00:00:38,580
collective worldview of the people

12
00:00:40,860 --> 00:00:45,520
that lets them understand
the reality around them.

13
00:00:45,840 --> 00:00:48,020
So another idea that

14
00:00:48,020 --> 00:00:52,300
we can say is mythology
is a shared reality.

15
00:00:53,360 --> 00:00:57,320
And every civilization has mythology.

16
00:00:57,480 --> 00:00:58,680
So, for example,

17
00:00:58,800 --> 00:01:02,320
today our mythology would be science

18
00:01:03,160 --> 00:01:04,980
and history, right?

19
00:01:05,200 --> 00:01:07,240
We think they are true and objective,

20
00:01:07,660 --> 00:01:09,700
but they're actually mythologies.

21
00:01:09,880 --> 00:01:12,460
They're a shared reality. And

22
00:01:12,460 --> 00:01:14,860
every civilization would
have its own mythology.

23
00:01:15,200 --> 00:01:18,260
And that's what makes the culture unique.

24
00:01:18,540 --> 00:01:21,340
Okay? So that's the first point. So

25
00:01:21,340 --> 00:01:26,700
what we will do today to better
understand Mesopotamia is to compare

26
00:01:26,700 --> 00:01:30,580
and contrast its mythology
with that of the Egyptians.

27
00:01:31,420 --> 00:01:33,820
Okay? Second point is

28
00:01:36,760 --> 00:01:41,460
there's an idea called the dialectic. And

29
00:01:41,460 --> 00:01:47,200
this was an idea proposed by the German philosopher
named Frederick Hegel in the 19th century.

30
00:01:47,460 --> 00:01:49,180
He believes that

31
00:01:49,180 --> 00:01:53,600
history is driven by opposing ideas.

32
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:58,420
So whenever you have one
mythology or one idea,

33
00:01:58,840 --> 00:02:02,760
there always must arise
another opposing idea

34
00:02:02,760 --> 00:02:04,120
that challenges it.

35
00:02:04,660 --> 00:02:05,940
And that's what drives history.

36
00:02:06,400 --> 00:02:12,060
And history is always moving
towards a synthesis of ideas.

37
00:02:12,940 --> 00:02:16,320
Okay? So the example would
be there's capitalism,

38
00:02:16,580 --> 00:02:18,440
and the opposing idea would be communism.

39
00:02:18,800 --> 00:02:22,940
And the synthesis of the
idea would be socialism.

40
00:02:23,020 --> 00:02:26,820
Okay? And what's really
important to understand

41
00:02:27,300 --> 00:02:31,280
is that ideas can be living things

42
00:02:31,280 --> 00:02:33,040
that change over time.

43
00:02:35,300 --> 00:02:38,920
The third idea I want to introduce is the

44
00:02:39,380 --> 00:02:42,660
idea of diversity and differentiation.

45
00:02:44,880 --> 00:02:46,980
And the idea here is

46
00:02:48,540 --> 00:02:53,220
we humans have some
fundamental natures about us.

47
00:02:53,340 --> 00:02:57,880
So for example, we're all
religious in some aspect.

48
00:03:00,640 --> 00:03:02,320
Another fundamental

49
00:03:03,400 --> 00:03:06,960
instinct about us, we
strive to be different.

50
00:03:07,440 --> 00:03:12,800
And that's why diversity
is the iron law of society.

51
00:03:13,440 --> 00:03:17,560
Okay? So the example is in a family,

52
00:03:17,760 --> 00:03:20,480
all the siblings will be different.

53
00:03:22,520 --> 00:03:25,960
In a classroom, the
students will be different.

54
00:03:27,580 --> 00:03:31,380
And you could be a certain
way in a classroom,

55
00:03:32,500 --> 00:03:35,440
and then you go to another classroom

56
00:03:35,440 --> 00:03:38,540
and you figure out the students
there are similar to you,

57
00:03:38,640 --> 00:03:42,620
so you will change as a person to
differentiate yourself from other people.

58
00:03:43,220 --> 00:03:47,940
Okay? So that's also another
principle of history.

59
00:03:48,300 --> 00:03:51,960
Societies strive to be
different from each other.

60
00:03:52,080 --> 00:03:54,460
They strive for diversity
and differentiation.

61
00:03:56,080 --> 00:03:59,060
We cannot make generalizations
about societies.

62
00:03:59,400 --> 00:04:01,580
The only thing that we can say is

63
00:04:02,680 --> 00:04:05,580
societies or cultures
fall into a spectrum.

64
00:04:06,840 --> 00:04:08,160
Okay? And

65
00:04:08,160 --> 00:04:09,480
they're usually defined by

66
00:04:09,480 --> 00:04:14,420
the elite or generalizations.

67
00:04:14,420 --> 00:04:17,580
So this is another way of saying today I'm

68
00:04:17,580 --> 00:04:22,680
going to make very broad
generalizations about these societies

69
00:04:22,680 --> 00:04:24,780
and generalizations. And

70
00:04:24,780 --> 00:04:29,220
they're useful for our purposes,

71
00:04:29,340 --> 00:04:31,380
but I want you to be aware that

72
00:04:31,380 --> 00:04:34,900
these are simplifications,
these are generalizations.

73
00:04:35,400 --> 00:04:36,720
Okay? Alright.

74
00:04:36,980 --> 00:04:38,440
So let's start.

75
00:04:38,720 --> 00:04:40,360
Okay. So

76
00:04:40,360 --> 00:04:44,880
Mesopotamia is a very different culture

77
00:04:44,880 --> 00:04:49,660
and civilization than Egypt
because of its geography.

78
00:04:50,200 --> 00:04:54,500
Okay? So if you look at
the geography of Egypt,

79
00:04:54,740 --> 00:04:58,200
it has natural boundaries.

80
00:04:58,540 --> 00:05:01,160
So for example, to the

81
00:05:02,100 --> 00:05:03,640
west is the Sahara Desert.

82
00:05:04,040 --> 00:05:07,200
To the north is the Mediterranean Sea.

83
00:05:09,360 --> 00:05:14,740
To the east is the Red Sea.

84
00:05:15,220 --> 00:05:19,880
Okay? And then to the
south are the Cataracts.

85
00:05:20,100 --> 00:05:22,620
So it makes it hard to travel up the Nile

86
00:05:23,200 --> 00:05:24,480
from the south.

87
00:05:24,920 --> 00:05:29,320
So there are really only two
access points into Egypt,

88
00:05:29,440 --> 00:05:30,900
which can be easily defended.

89
00:05:30,980 --> 00:05:33,780
The south and also from the Levant,

90
00:05:33,900 --> 00:05:36,840
which is basically Israel, Syria, Jordan.

91
00:05:38,300 --> 00:05:41,540
And because of its natural boundaries,

92
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:47,240
Egypt doesn't really feel
threatened by external enemies,

93
00:05:47,460 --> 00:05:51,220
right? Also, it has the Nile River,

94
00:05:51,400 --> 00:05:54,560
which is the foundation
of its civilization.

95
00:05:55,340 --> 00:06:01,240
Remember last class we talked about
how the Nile was very generous.

96
00:06:01,320 --> 00:06:04,000
It flooded predictably every season,

97
00:06:04,180 --> 00:06:08,480
and so it made agriculture very productive

98
00:06:09,090 --> 00:06:10,940
in Egypt, which

99
00:06:10,940 --> 00:06:14,140
allowed them to sustain
a very large population,

100
00:06:14,540 --> 00:06:16,040
which then

101
00:06:16,040 --> 00:06:19,500
can be used to create
monuments like the pyramid.

102
00:06:20,850 --> 00:06:24,760
So for most of its
history, Egypt was stable

103
00:06:24,760 --> 00:06:26,280
and prosperous.

104
00:06:29,320 --> 00:06:32,140
Mesopotamia is completely different.

105
00:06:32,140 --> 00:06:34,320
So first of all,

106
00:06:34,380 --> 00:06:36,460
Mesopotamia, which

107
00:06:36,460 --> 00:06:39,560
is in what we call Iraq today,

108
00:06:39,780 --> 00:06:42,740
it has no natural boundaries.

109
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:47,640
Mesopotamia is Greek for
the land between two rivers.

110
00:06:47,880 --> 00:06:50,720
These two rivers are the Euphrates

111
00:06:50,720 --> 00:06:52,720
and the Tigris.

112
00:06:58,560 --> 00:07:00,080
To the

113
00:07:02,680 --> 00:07:06,500
west of Mesopotamia would be Arabia,

114
00:07:06,720 --> 00:07:08,760
and the Levant, okay?

115
00:07:09,020 --> 00:07:11,500
To the north would be Anatolia.

116
00:07:13,640 --> 00:07:18,240
To the east are the Zagos Mountains.

117
00:07:20,240 --> 00:07:24,100
The thing about Anatolia is it

118
00:07:24,100 --> 00:07:28,060
itself is a very prosperous place.

119
00:07:28,240 --> 00:07:33,100
So it will become eventually
home to certain empires,

120
00:07:33,180 --> 00:07:35,980
like the Hittites, who

121
00:07:35,980 --> 00:07:39,580
will always threaten Mesopotamia, okay?

122
00:07:39,800 --> 00:07:42,500
So Anatolia is a threat to Mesopotamia.

123
00:07:43,700 --> 00:07:46,860
The people of Arabia and

124
00:07:46,860 --> 00:07:49,740
the Zagos Mountains are nomads.

125
00:07:49,860 --> 00:07:53,940
And as we know, nomads are
a very aggressive people.

126
00:07:54,280 --> 00:07:59,000
And so they will constantly
launch raids against Mesopotamia,

127
00:07:59,140 --> 00:08:00,820
which threatens its safety.

128
00:08:01,120 --> 00:08:03,240
Okay? So,

129
00:08:06,040 --> 00:08:08,420
Mesopotamia throughout its history

130
00:08:09,240 --> 00:08:12,820
has always been at war with its neighbors.

131
00:08:15,660 --> 00:08:18,800
The other thing about Mesopotamia is,

132
00:08:20,200 --> 00:08:24,100
even though it's fertile, it's part of
something called a fertile crescent,

133
00:08:24,180 --> 00:08:28,320
okay, which extends from
Mesopotamia into the Levant, okay?

134
00:08:28,400 --> 00:08:30,160
It's called a fertile crescent.

135
00:08:33,280 --> 00:08:37,600
The Euphrates and the Tigris
don't really cooperate.

136
00:08:38,540 --> 00:08:41,800
They're very chaotic. They
change course all the time.

137
00:08:42,420 --> 00:08:46,260
And so, the only way to tame the Euphrates

138
00:08:46,260 --> 00:08:48,360
and the Tigris is through irrigation.

139
00:08:49,180 --> 00:08:52,900
Okay? Because if you farm
too close to the bed,

140
00:08:52,900 --> 00:08:55,140
the river bank, you're
going to get flooded.

141
00:08:55,420 --> 00:09:00,200
Okay? So they have to develop irrigation in
order to tame the Euphrates and the Tigris.

142
00:09:06,520 --> 00:09:09,340
Okay. So, the geography,

143
00:09:09,820 --> 00:09:12,880
all these two cultures are very different,

144
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:14,640
and therefore the history
is very different.

145
00:09:14,860 --> 00:09:16,200
For most of its history,

146
00:09:16,640 --> 00:09:18,460
Egypt was unified as an empire.

147
00:09:18,700 --> 00:09:20,700
It was very stable. But

148
00:09:20,700 --> 00:09:25,420
Mesopotamia was always in flux, okay?

149
00:09:25,500 --> 00:09:30,220
So the first great civilization
of Mesopotamia were the Sumerians.

150
00:09:30,440 --> 00:09:32,920
They were eventually
conquered by the Akkadians.

151
00:09:33,200 --> 00:09:35,880
And then you have the
Assyrians and the Babylonians.

152
00:09:36,640 --> 00:09:41,240
And these four civilizations
are what we call Mesopotamia,

153
00:09:41,340 --> 00:09:49,540
okay? Okay? Okay, any questions so

154
00:09:49,540 --> 00:09:53,160
far before I go into the
brief history of Mesopotamia?

155
00:10:01,100 --> 00:10:03,080
Okay, yeah, that's a good question, okay.

156
00:10:03,220 --> 00:10:05,100
But what is the relationship
between these four relationships?

157
00:10:05,320 --> 00:10:06,800
The Sumerians, the Akkadians,

158
00:10:08,680 --> 00:10:10,340
the Babylonians, and the Assyrians.

159
00:10:10,340 --> 00:10:14,380
Okay, so the very first
civilization were the Sumerians.

160
00:10:15,180 --> 00:10:18,440
And then they were eventually
united by the Akkadians.

161
00:10:19,380 --> 00:10:21,760
Okay, so Sumeria was not really an empire,

162
00:10:22,020 --> 00:10:24,500
it was a culture and a civilization that

163
00:10:24,500 --> 00:10:29,400
was divided into city -states, like the Greeks
before the conquest of the Macedonians.

164
00:10:30,340 --> 00:10:33,500
And the Akkadians under Sargon of Akkad,

165
00:10:33,580 --> 00:10:38,660
or Sargon the Great,
united the city -states,

166
00:10:38,660 --> 00:10:43,220
and gave us the idea of
Sumerian civilization.

167
00:10:44,770 --> 00:10:46,320
After the Akkadian Empire fell,

168
00:10:46,940 --> 00:10:50,100
North Mesopotamia became
the Assyrian Empire,

169
00:10:50,460 --> 00:10:52,800
South Mesopotamia became
the Babylonian Empire.

170
00:10:53,080 --> 00:10:57,300
They all saw themselves as heirs
to the Sumerian civilization.

171
00:10:57,840 --> 00:11:01,000
So even though they're
different civilizations,

172
00:11:01,320 --> 00:11:03,520
they share a common mythology,

173
00:11:03,880 --> 00:11:06,060
okay, which I will discuss
later in the class.

174
00:11:08,660 --> 00:11:11,520
Okay, does that make
sense? Great, okay, so

175
00:11:11,520 --> 00:11:13,460
I'm gonna talk very briefly

176
00:11:14,120 --> 00:11:17,180
about how Mesopotamia developed,

177
00:11:17,640 --> 00:11:20,820
okay? So, remember

178
00:11:20,820 --> 00:11:22,780
that in the beginning,

179
00:11:22,940 --> 00:11:26,120
agriculture first appeared in two places,

180
00:11:27,360 --> 00:11:30,220
Anatolia and the Levant, okay?

181
00:11:31,280 --> 00:11:33,720
Then there was something called the

182
00:11:33,720 --> 00:11:38,500
8.2 kilo year event.

183
00:11:38,660 --> 00:11:42,160
And we can see this as
dramatic climate change.

184
00:11:43,660 --> 00:11:47,660
That radically changed the geography

185
00:11:47,660 --> 00:11:52,040
and the climate of this world,

186
00:11:52,200 --> 00:11:53,580
okay?

187
00:11:54,140 --> 00:11:56,600
And because of the
cooling and temperature,

188
00:11:56,960 --> 00:12:01,540
the people in the Levant, and the people
in Anatolia were forced to spread out.

189
00:12:01,700 --> 00:12:04,320
So they went to Europe,
they went to Egypt,

190
00:12:04,420 --> 00:12:06,520
they went to Mesopotamia.

191
00:12:08,660 --> 00:12:11,520
And when they did that,
they spread agriculture.

192
00:12:13,440 --> 00:12:16,180
And remember, the
agriculture, the mythology,

193
00:12:16,460 --> 00:12:19,080
is the mother goddess, which meant that

194
00:12:19,080 --> 00:12:21,920
they were mainly peaceful,

195
00:12:22,730 --> 00:12:27,260
egalitarian people, okay,
who were very artistic.

196
00:12:27,540 --> 00:12:31,160
So this is a very peaceful, stable world.

197
00:12:33,680 --> 00:12:38,640
But then, you have the
5.9 kilo year event,

198
00:12:38,640 --> 00:12:42,420
year event. This is about 6,000 years ago,

199
00:12:42,560 --> 00:12:44,700
4,000 BCE.

200
00:12:45,180 --> 00:12:49,100
And again, you saw a radical change

201
00:12:50,100 --> 00:12:53,900
in temperature, which

202
00:12:53,900 --> 00:12:56,880
again forced migration

203
00:12:56,880 --> 00:12:57,920
and

204
00:12:57,920 --> 00:13:00,440
forced these

205
00:13:00,440 --> 00:13:04,440
civilizations to change.

206
00:13:04,440 --> 00:13:06,720
One of the major

207
00:13:06,720 --> 00:13:11,460
changes in Mesopotamia

208
00:13:11,460 --> 00:13:13,260
is the founding of

209
00:13:13,260 --> 00:13:17,780
a place called Uruk.

210
00:13:17,940 --> 00:13:21,420
Uruk is interesting because

211
00:13:21,420 --> 00:13:27,240
it is considered the
first city of the world.

212
00:13:27,540 --> 00:13:30,600
And so this is the beginning
of what we call civilization,

213
00:13:31,100 --> 00:13:33,220
the modern idea of civilization.

214
00:13:34,440 --> 00:13:39,580
And that's about 40,000 people. And

215
00:13:39,580 --> 00:13:45,020
this is what we consider the beginning
of the Sumerian civilization.

216
00:13:48,700 --> 00:13:53,080
And the Sumerian civilization is
considered the cradle of civilization.

217
00:13:53,520 --> 00:13:58,600
It is the beginning of the
foundations of modern civilization.

218
00:13:59,060 --> 00:14:00,620
They gave us irrigation technology.

219
00:14:01,080 --> 00:14:02,520
They gave us mathematics.

220
00:14:02,920 --> 00:14:07,080
They gave us astronomy. They gave
us writing, cuneiform writing.

221
00:14:07,300 --> 00:14:09,340
They gave us the legal system.

222
00:14:09,820 --> 00:14:11,180
They gave us

223
00:14:11,820 --> 00:14:14,640
hierarchy and religion. So

224
00:14:14,640 --> 00:14:19,420
there was an explosion of innovation
with the founding of Uruk.

225
00:14:20,320 --> 00:14:24,200
Now Uruk eventually
would become a huge city,

226
00:14:24,320 --> 00:14:27,840
which compelled the people to migrate

227
00:14:27,840 --> 00:14:31,140
and found cities that are similar to Uruk.

228
00:14:31,360 --> 00:14:35,980
They're basically colonies. And they're
scattered throughout Mesopotamia.

229
00:14:36,080 --> 00:14:39,120
These are city -states that

230
00:14:39,120 --> 00:14:42,220
at first were part of
the Uruk civilization.

231
00:14:42,720 --> 00:14:46,080
But eventually they became prosperous

232
00:14:46,080 --> 00:14:49,920
and wealthy themselves.

233
00:14:50,220 --> 00:14:52,600
And so they broke away from Uruk.

234
00:14:52,720 --> 00:14:55,800
And this led to tension and

235
00:14:55,800 --> 00:14:59,560
conflict and maybe sometimes
even outright warfare.

236
00:15:00,080 --> 00:15:02,360
But please remember, during this time,

237
00:15:02,560 --> 00:15:05,460
the idea of the Uruk, the Uruk
civilization, was massive warfare that

238
00:15:05,460 --> 00:15:07,500
we would see during the
Greek and Roman periods.

239
00:15:07,660 --> 00:15:09,920
It's still pretty
absent. There's conflict.

240
00:15:10,140 --> 00:15:11,600
It's short -term.

241
00:15:11,800 --> 00:15:15,140
And they have conflicts
in order to resolve

242
00:15:15,920 --> 00:15:18,420
like territorial disputes
or trade disputes.

243
00:15:18,700 --> 00:15:19,980
But they're not trying
to wipe each other out.

244
00:15:24,400 --> 00:15:28,040
One of the great mysteries is

245
00:15:28,040 --> 00:15:29,620
where the Sumerians come from.

246
00:15:29,940 --> 00:15:32,560
We have this problem because when

247
00:15:32,560 --> 00:15:36,320
we discovered cuneiform, and we
translated the Sumerian language,

248
00:15:36,580 --> 00:15:40,020
we discovered the spoken language is

249
00:15:40,020 --> 00:15:43,780
very different from
the surrounding regions

250
00:15:43,780 --> 00:15:45,820
who spoke something
called a Semitic language.

251
00:15:46,100 --> 00:15:50,100
So the languages spoken in the area
are part of a Semitic language group.

252
00:15:50,360 --> 00:15:53,800
But Sumerian is not part of that group.

253
00:15:53,940 --> 00:15:55,240
There's not enough similarities.

254
00:15:56,280 --> 00:16:00,200
Also, there is no other language

255
00:16:00,820 --> 00:16:03,220
like Sumerian in the world.

256
00:16:03,320 --> 00:16:05,960
Okay? It's what is called
a language isolate.

257
00:16:06,920 --> 00:16:08,280
It is unique.

258
00:16:11,340 --> 00:16:14,720
And so this has puzzled scholars

